deck: One of three prominent and hapless zombies in Zomboss's army, along with his compatriots Tugboat and Frogpants.
description:
Character Description

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom are the most prominent zombies in Zomboss’s army, showing up in most of his plans. Like the Three Stooges, they are completely hapless, always getting into trouble, screwing up the plans, and getting picked on by Zomboss.

Nigel Blimpbottom is a Buckethead zombie. He wears a metal pail on his head, inscribed with the handwritten name, “Nigel.” He wears a pink shirt, yellow vest, and blue pants.

Unlike his compatriots Tugboat and Frogpants, Nigel cannot (or at least, has not yet to date) say his name, and can presumably only say “brains” like other zombies.

Major Story Arcs

Bully for You

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom, in disguise, help steal supplies from a hardware store for Zomboss’s newest evil invention.

The Emptiness

In this back-up story, the group, once again in disguise, goes through great difficulty to find some Pop Smarts for Zomboss, becoming very hungry themselves. However, he won’t give them any.

Grown Sweet Home

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel are among the zombies that Zomboss trains to be human, using tips surreptitiously picked up from Patrice and Nate.

They are then part of the invading army Zomboss sends against Neighborville, and part of the parade of zombies that walks through the town, incognito.

As part of a series of individual battles, Nigel fights Jeff the Bloomerang, and loses.

Tugboat steals some of Zomboss’s Pop Smarts, which Nate and Patrice see on surveillance cameras. (Frogpants and Nigel apparently also help to steal the Pop Smarts but we don’t see them do it on panel.)

Later, the kids tell Zomboss that Tugboat, Nigel, and Frogpants stole the Pop Smarts, which turns Zomboss into a rage. He sets the rest of the zombies on the trio. Later the three are seen walking out of town, clothes in disarray, with signs proclaiming, “Zomboss iz a gerk!”, “We needz a place of our owns,” and “Zomboss unfairzz!”

Petal to the Metal

Nigel is seen testing out Echo Canyon during the race between the plants and zombies.

The three are part of the invasion force in Neighborville, which Zomboss is trying to use the race to distract the kids and plants from. However, Frogpants gets tangled up in the cord to the TV that Zomboss is using to explain his plan to the zombies, and accidentally turns the TV off. Without knowing Zomboss’s plan, the zombies basically just hang out instead of invading.

Boom Boom Mushroom

The trio is part of Zomboss’s cavern invasion force, taking over the caves below Neighborville. However all three of them screw up somehow, keeping the army from carrying out their plan on time.

Nigel leaves the popcorn machine on too long, creating a huge pile of popcorn that blocks the zombie army from attacking the town.

Tugboat and Nigel get passed over as “best zombie” in favor of Mr. Stubbins.

When Zomboss is finally ready to carry out his plan, he finds out that Nate and Twister switched his technology around, and the zombies are lifted up into the town instead of vice versa. Tugboat and Nigel are among the zombies lifted to the surface.

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom are the most prominent zombies in Zomboss’s army, showing up in most of his plans. Like the Three Stooges, they are completely hapless, always getting into trouble, screwing up the plans, and getting picked on by Zomboss.

Tugboat is a normal zombie in the typical zombie clothes of a brown suit jacket, striped red and white tie, white shirt, and blue pants. There are many other zombies who look exactly the same as him, and he is only identifiable when he is with the more easily-recognized Frogpants and Nigel.

Unlike almost all other zombies, who can only say “brains,” Tugboat can say his name, “Tugboat.”

Major Story Arcs

Bully for You

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom, in disguise, help steal supplies from a hardware store for Zomboss’s newest evil invention.

In this back-up story, the group, once again in disguise, goes through great difficulty to find some Pop Smarts for Zomboss, becoming very hungry themselves. However, he won’t give them any.

They are then part of the invading army Zomboss sends against Neighborville, and part of the parade of zombies that walks through the town, incognito.

As part of a series of individual battles, Tugboat fights Grrawrr-Bear the Ultimate Face-Puncher, but loses.

Tugboat steals some of Zomboss’s Pop Smarts, which Nate and Patrice see on surveillance cameras. (Frogpants and Nigel apparently also help to steal the Pop Smarts but we don’t see them do it on panel.)

Later, the kids tell Zomboss that Tugboat, Nigel, and Frogpants stole the Pop Smarts, which turns Zomboss into a rage. He sets the rest of the zombies on the trio. Later the three are seen walking out of town, clothes in disarray, with signs proclaiming, “Zomboss iz a gerk!”, “We needz a place of our owns,” and “Zomboss unfairzz!”

Pedal to the Metal

Tugboat is seen holding a sign at the city limits of Neighborville, noting that it is the site of the occasional zombie invasion.

The three are part of the invasion force in Neighborville, which Zomboss is trying to use the race to distract the kids and plants from. However, Frogpants gets tangled up in the cord to the TV that Zomboss is using to explain his plan to the zombies, and accidentally turns the TV off. Without knowing Zomboss’s plan, the zombies basically just hang out instead of invading.

Boom Boom Mushroom

The trio is part of Zomboss’s cavern invasion force, taking over the caves below Neighborville. However all three of them screw up somehow, keeping the army from carrying out their plan on time.

Tugboat uses the hydraulics from the elevator that Zomboss was going to use to drop the town into the caverns. Tugboat puts the hydraulics onto an actual tugboat to make a jacked-up boat.

Tugboat and Nigel get passed over as “best zombie” in favor of Mr. Stubbins.

When Zomboss is finally ready to carry out his plan, he finds out that Nate and Twister switched his technology around, and the zombies are lifted up into the town instead of vice versa. Tugboat and Nigel are among the zombies lifted to the surface.

deck: One of three prominent and hapless zombies in Zomboss's army, along with his compatriots Tugboat and Nigel Blimpbottom.
description:
Character Description

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom are the most prominent zombies in Zomboss’s army, showing up in most of his plans. Like the Three Stooges, they are completely hapless, always getting into trouble, screwing up the plans, and getting picked on by Zomboss.

Frogpants is a normal zombie, and can be identified by his green shirt with a big drawing of a frog on it, and his orange pants that are covered by smaller drawings of the same frog.

Unlike almost all other zombies, who can only say “brains,” Frogpants can say his name, “Frogpants” or “Frogpantz.”

Major Story Arcs

Bully for You

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel Blimpbottom, in disguise, help steal supplies from a hardware store for Zomboss’s newest evil invention.

The Emptiness

In this back-up story, the group, once again in disguise, goes through great difficulty to find some Pop Smarts for Zomboss, becoming very hungry themselves. However, he won’t give them any.

Grown Sweet Home

Frogpants, Tugboat, and Nigel are among the zombies that Zomboss trains to be human, using tips surreptitiously picked up from Patrice and Nate.

They are then part of the invading army Zomboss sends against Neighborville, and part of the parade of zombies that walks through the town, incognito.

As part of a series of individual battles, Frogpants dances against a sunflower in a contest, and wins.

Tugboat steals some of Zomboss’s Pop Smarts, which Nate and Patrice see on surveillance cameras. (Frogpants and Nigel apparently also help to steal the Pop Smarts but we don’t see them do it on panel.)

Later, the kids tell Zomboss that Tugboat, Nigel, and Frogpants stole the Pop Smarts, which turns Zomboss into a rage. He sets the rest of the zombies on the trio. Later the three are seen walking out of town, clothes in disarray, with signs proclaiming, “Zomboss iz a gerk!”, “We needz a place of our owns,” and “Zomboss unfairzz!”

Pedal to the Metal

Frogpants gets a picture of Zomboss as a reward, but is also kicked by his boot-kicking machine. Later, he is shown in the Zomboss’s personal race car in the race between the plants and zombies.

The three are part of the invasion force in Neighborville, which Zomboss is trying to use the race to distract the kids and plants from. However, Frogpants gets tangled up in the cord to the TV that Zomboss is using to explain his plan to the zombies, and accidentally turns the TV off. Without knowing Zomboss’s plan, the zombies basically just hang out instead of invading.

Frogpants is part of the welcome party for Zomboss’s return from the race.

Boom Boom Mushroom

The trio is part of Zomboss’s cavern invasion force, taking over the caves below Neighborville. However all three of them screw up somehow, keeping the army from carrying out their plan on time.

Frogpants trips over the wires they run to the surface to get power, and gets completely tangled up from head to toe. He tries to turn on the power to the toaster so Zomboss can make some Pop Smarts, but it shorts and he fries himself. Zomboss later puts a TV in front of him with a video of Zomboss scowling, to help motivate Frogpants into freeing himself, but it doesn’t work.

When Zomboss is finally ready to carry out his plan, he finds out that Nate and Twister switched his technology around, and the zombies are lifted up into the town instead of vice versa. Tugboat and Nigel are among the zombies lifted to the surface. Frogpants, still tied up in cords, gets snarled by some of the jogging bulls that are racing through town, and bounces along after them.

Toasted

In this back-up story, Zomboss puts Frogpants onto a kite with some Pop Smarts and flies him up into the air to be hit by lightning as an attempt to find alternate ways to cook Pop Smarts.

deck: An activist against Doctor Doom.
description:
Cosette Lafarge is the daughter of Professor Lafarge and when she was a kid she was taken hostage by Victor von Doom in order to get her father to work of missile silo's for him. She was eventually able to flee Latveria thanks to the resistance within the country.

Later she along with a handful of other people were protesting the Latverian Embassy being in New York. The protest got violent and led to Cosette getting injured, luckily Dr. Donald Blake was there to assist her. Cosette told him of her predicament with Doom and her father which led Blake to tell her that he'd get Thor to assist her.

Thor went into Latveria to save Professor Lafarge but in reality he didn't care for his daughter and simply assisted Doom for the money. Upon Thor's return he bent the truth to Corsette, simply stating that he died doing what he loved and that she was the last thing he spoke of.

deck: A young boy recruited by Christine Trelane of The Monarchy. Gaining superpowers but ended up used and abused by other kids who he gave abilities to by mistake.
description:
Origin

The boy who would become Matthew was once an elementary school student who had the terrible run of luck due to a multiversal ripple effect which had skewed his destiny of a happy healthy life with his loving family. While on a bus trip an accident occurs where a truck carrying nuclear isotopic rods capsizes in transit, jettisoning them from its storage container and lodging them into the poor kids chest.

The Authoriteens

When he woke up Matt found he had gained tremendous yet uncontrollable powers from the event which a couple of classmates exploited him for, turning violent and destructive. Basing themselves off of The Authority the group used the powers given to them by Matthew in order to terrorize the projects that they lived in.

With their diminutive benefactor tailing behind them all the way as he crept along in pain due to the instability of his powers. But when he tried to dissuade their murderous crusade, they turned on him and beat him to near death.

Until the timely arrival of Christine Trelane and the rest of her covert superhero group called The Monarchy. As he lay unconscious Matthews powers were spiraling out of control, Christine guessed he would detonate with ten times the force of what devastated Hiroshima during WWII. With the quick thinking of reverend Jon Farmer his energy output was dispersed into a harmless chromatic shower of energy saving both him and the city from certain annihilation.

Joining The Monarchy

After some months in the hospital and back at home with his mother, Matt was once again met By Ms. Trelane in his room while reading comics. She reminds him of events that brought the two of them together as well as how he received his powers. While going over how he came into his abilities, she gives him a retelling of events which played out with her team during their invasion of Chimera's world. After finishing her story she takes him to their new mobile reality shift-ship called The Throne, integrating him into their new alt. reality peacekeeping black ops.

Powers & Abilities

Matthew is an incredibly powerful SPB (Super Powered Being) with abilities garnered from nucleo/irradiant control rods are lodged into his sternum mere inches from rending his heart. Due to his lack of experience he would unintentionally pulsate with power that had odd and often destructive effects on his Surroundings.

Superpower Manipulation

The core of his abilities is the bestowal or activation, cancellation and erasure of enhanced abilities within another living being. He has yet to fully harness and control these abilities as of yet seeing as he had given them to four of his former school friends without intent to.

Powers bestowed

  • Laser Vision
  • Energy Infusion
  • Hand Blasts
  • Enhanced Strength

Energy Manipulation

Matt can also unleash highly destructive ergokinetic discharge which theoretically could unleash incredible devastating force. Force enough to wipe a small cityscape clean off the map.
